    <subsection xml:id="ss_poly_powerseries">
    <title>Polynomials and power series</title>
    <p>
        Whereas normally power series are introduced as a sort of generalization of polynomials, we will take the approach of defining the notion of a ring of power series, and identify a subring as the ring of polynomials. 
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="spec_power_series">
    <title>Power series ring</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a nontrivial commutative ring. We define the set <m>R[[x]]</m> to be the set of all formal sums of the form
    <md>
        <mrow> \sum_{n=0}^\infty a_n x^n \amp </mrow>
    </md>,
    where <m>a_n\in R</m> for all <m>n\in \Z_{\geq 0}</m>, and we define binary operations <m>+</m> and <m>\cdot</m> as follows: 
    <md>
        <mrow>\sum_{n=0}^\infty a_nx^n+\sum_{n=0}^\infty b_nx^n \amp = \sum_{n=0}^\infty (a_n+b_n)x^n</mrow>
        <mrow>\sum_{n=0}^\infty a_nx^n\cdot \sum_{n=0}^\infty b_nx^n \amp = \sum_{n=0}^\infty c_nx^n \amp c_n=\sum_{k=0}^n a_k b_{n-k}</mrow>
    </md>.
    The triple <m>(R[[x]], +,\cdot)</m> is a commutative ring called the <term>power series ring over (or with coefficients in) <m>R</m> in the unknown (or indeterminate) <m>x</m></term>. The additive and multiplicative identities of <m>R[[x]]</m> are given as
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow>0 \amp =\sum_{n=0}^\infty 0x^n = 0+0x+0x^2+\cdots </mrow>
        <mrow>1 \amp =1x^0+\sum_{n=1}^\infty 0x^n =1+0x+0x^2+\cdots </mrow>
    </md>.
  Given a power series <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty</m>, we call <m>a_nx^n</m> its <term><m>n</m>-th term</term>, and <m>a_n</m> its  <term><m>n</m>-th coefficient</term>.
    </p>
<p> 
    We will use function-like notation to name power series. In more detail, we will refer to power series using function letters like <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>, and will write <m>f(x)=\sum_{n=0}^\infty a_nx_n</m> when explicitly introducing names of coefficients.
</p>
    </statement>
    </activity>
    <remark>
        <title>Power series equality</title>
    <p>
        When are two power series <m>f(x)=\sum_{n=0}^\infty a_nx^n</m> and <m>g(x)=\sum_{n=0}^\infty b_nx^n</m> equal? Identifying these formal sums as tuples <m>(a_n)_{n=0}^\infty</m>, <m>(b_n)_{n=0}^\infty</m>, following <xref ref="fiat_formal_sums"/>, we see that 
        <md number="no">
           <mrow> f=g \iff a_n=b_n \text{ for all } n\in \Z_{\geq 0}</mrow>
        </md>.
    </p>
    </remark>
    
    <p>
        We now identify the ring <m>R[x]</m> of polynomials over <m>R</m> as the subring of <m>R[[x]]</m> consisting of all power series whose coefficients are <q>eventually</q> equal to zero. 
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="spec_poly_ring">
    <title>Polynomial rings</title>
    <statement>
   <p>
  Let <m>R</m> be a nontrivial commutative ring.
  Define the <term>polynomial ring over <m>R</m> in the indeterminate <m>x</m></term> to be the subset <m>R[x]\subseteq R[[x]]</m> of all power series whose coefficients are <em>eventually</em> equal to zero: i.e., 
  <md>
    <mrow>R[x] \amp = \{f(x)=\sum_{n=0}^\infty a_nx^n\in R[[x]]\mid a_n=0 \text{ for all } n&gt;  N \text{ for some } N\in \Z_{\geq 0} \} </mrow>
    <mrow> \amp =\{f\in R[[x]]\mid f(x)=\sum_{n=0}^Na_nx^n \text{ for some } N\in \Z_{\geq 0}, a_n\in R\}</mrow>
  </md>.
  It is easy to see that <m>R[x]</m> is a subring of <m>R[[x]]</m>, and thus a ring in its own right. Restricted to <m>R[x]</m>, the power series multiplication rule becomes the familiar polynomial multiplication rule: 
  <md>
    <mrow>(\anpoly)\amp \cdot (\bmpoly) =\sum_{k=0}^{m+n}c_kx^k</mrow>
     <mrow>c_k\amp =\sum_{j=0}^k a_j b_{k-j}</mrow>
  </md>.
  As illustrated above, when denoting polynomials we will usually drop all the terms with zero coefficients: <eg/>,  <m>f(x)=a_0+a_1x+\cdots +a_nx^n</m>, or <m>f(x)=\anpoly</m>.
</p>

<p>
  Given a nonzero polynomial <m>f\in R[x]</m>, we define its <term>degree</term>, <m>\deg f</m>, to be the smallest <m>n</m> satisfying <m>a_n\ne 0</m>.
  If <m>f(x) = 0</m>, we define <m>\deg f=-\infty</m>.
</p>

<p>
  If <m>f(x)=\anpoly</m> is a polynomial of degree <m>n\ne -\infty</m>, we call <m>a_{n}</m> the <term>leading coefficient</term> of <m>f</m>.
  A polynomial with leading coefficient equal to <m>1\in R</m> is called <term>monic</term>.
</p>
    </statement>
    </activity>
    </subsection>
    <subsection xml:id="ss_quaternions">
    <title>Quaternion rings</title>
    <activity xml:id="spec_quat_rings">
    <title>Quaternion rings</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a nontrivial commutative ring. We define <m>H(R)</m> to be the set of all formal sums 
    <md>
        <mrow>a_1+a_2i+a_3j+a_4k</mrow>
    </md>,
    where <m>a_i\in R</m> for all <m>1\leq i\leq 4</m>. We define addition on <m>H(R)</m> as 
    <md>
        <mrow>(a_1+a_2i+a_3j+a_4k)+(b_1+b_2i+b_3j+b_4k) </mrow>
        <mrow> = (a_1+b_1)+(a_2+b_2)i+(a_3+b_3)j+(a_4+b_4)k</mrow>
    </md>.
    We define multiplication to be the unique associative binary operation <m>\cdot</m> that distributes over the addition operation <m>+</m>, satisfies 
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow>b(a_1+a_2i+a_3j+a_4k) \amp =(a_1+a_2i+a_3j+a_4k)b </mrow>
        <mrow> \amp =ba_1+ba_2i+ba_3j+ba_4k</mrow>
    </md>
    for all 
    <md>
        <mrow>b \amp =b+0i+0j+0k\in H(R)</mrow>
    </md>,
    and satisfies 
    <md number="yes">
        <mrow> i^2\amp =j^2=k^2=-1 </mrow>
        <mrow>ij \amp = k, jk=i,  ki=j</mrow>
    </md>.
    The triple <m>(H(R), +, \cdot)</m> is a ring called the <term>quaternion ring over (or with coefficients in) <m>R</m></term>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        In the special case where <m>R=\R</m>, we denote <m>\HH=H(\R)</m> and call <m>\HH</m> the <term>Hamilton quaternions</term>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </activity>
    
    </subsection>
</section>